04804nam a2200769Ia 9780271097237DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20242024pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710972377 a10.1515/97802710972372doi  a(DE-B1597)691435  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aDS19 7aART0150902bisacsh04a950.22231 aDomínguez Torres, Mónica, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPearls for the Crown :bArt, Nature, and Race in the Age of Spanish Expansion /cMónica Domínguez Torres. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource (218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Pearls as Imperial Gems -- t1 Signs of Divine Power: Pearls and the Immaculate Conception in Habsburg Spain -- t2 Mastering Nature: Pearls, Natural History, and Artistic Practice in the Early Modern Spanish World -- t3 Contested Stories of Wealth: The Island of Pearls in “New World” Chronicles -- t4 A Pearl for the Grand Duke: Images of Native American Pearl Divers in Medici Florence -- t5 Pearl and Ebony Treasures: Precious Collectibles at the Court of Augustus the Strong -- tEpilogue: Pearls, Divers, and the Order of Nature -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the age of European expansion, pearls became potent symbols of imperial supremacy. Pearls for the Crown demonstrates how European art legitimated racialized hierarchies and inequitable notions about humanity and nature that still hold sway today.When Christopher Columbus encountered pristine pearl beds in southern Caribbean waters in 1498, he procured the first source of New World wealth for the Spanish Crown, but he also established an alternative path to an industry that had remained outside European control for centuries. Centering her study on a selection of key artworks tied to the pearl industry, Mónica Domínguez Torres examines the interplay of materiality, labor, race, and power that drove artistic production in the early modern period. Spanish colonizers exploited the expertise and forced labor of Native American and African workers to establish pearling centers along the coasts of South and Central America, disrupting the environmental and demographic dynamics of their overseas territories. Drawing from postcolonial theory, material culture studies, and ecocriticism, Domínguez Torres demonstrates how, through use of the pearl, European courtly art articulated ideas about imperial expansion, European superiority, and control over nature, all of which played key roles in the political circles surrounding the Spanish Crown.This highly anticipated interdisciplinary study will be welcomed by scholars of art history, the history of colonial Latin America, and ecocriticism in the context of the Spanish colonies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMongolsxHistory. 7aART / History / Baroque & Rococo.2bisacsh  aAugustus the Strong.  aCaribbean.  aColombia.  aCosimo II de’ Medici.  aCubagua Island.  aDresden.  aFlorence.  aGermany.  aImmaculate Conception.  aItaly.  aMargarita Island.  aNative American pearl divers.  aNatural History.  aNew World chronicles.  aPearl Coast.  aRiohacha.  aSpain.  aToledo.  aVenezuela.  ablack pearl divers.  aconstruction of identiy of the early modern Iberian and Latin American world.  alabor history.  apearl fishing.  apearls.  atrade.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271097237?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271097237423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271097237/orig